can, Judith Butler, Jean Laplanche, and Eve Kosofsky Sedgwick.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aModernism (Literature). 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 0aProtest literature. 0aPsychoanalysis in literature. 0aSpeech acts (Linguistics) in literature. 0aSubjectivity in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aavant garde.  abiopolitical.  acivil rights.  adecadent modernism.  aeuro american.  afrancophone arabic.  afree address.  afreedom of speech.  afreud.  ahuman rights.  aintersectional.  ajudith butler.  alacan.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary rant.  aliterary theory.  aliterary.  amodern history.  amodernism.  anonfiction.  aoscar wilde.  apolitical science.  apolitics of address.  apostcolonialism.  apsychoanalysis.  aqueer studies.  aredefinition.  aresistance.  arights.  aself expression.  aspeech.  asubjection.  atheoretical perspective.  athought provoking.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025925640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094579140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945791423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520945791/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY